{{nihongo|'''Nagaoka-kyō'''|長岡京}} was the [[:en:Capital of Japan|Capital of Japan]] from 784 to 794. Its location was in [[Otokuni District, Kyoto|Otokuni District]], [[Yamashiro Province]], corresponding to a 4.3 x 5.3 kilometer area spanning the borders of modern cities of [[Mukō, Kyoto|Mukō]] and [[:en:Nagaokakyō, Kyoto|Nagaokakyō, Kyoto]], the town of [[:en:Ōyamazaki|Ōyamazaki]], and the [[Nishikyō-ku, Kyoto|Nishikyō-ku]] ward of the city of [[:en:Kyoto|Kyoto]]. The ruins of the palace have been found in the Kaidecho neighbourhood of the city of Mukō and have been designated as a [[Monuments of Japan|National Historic Site]] since 1964, with the area under protection expanded in 2016. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://kunishitei.bunka.go.jp/heritage/detail/401/1720|title=長岡京跡 |language=Japanese |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=}}</ref>
